INSERT INTO specialty_faqs (specialty_slug, category, question, answer, short_answer, priority, search_keywords) VALUES
('general', 'coding', 'How do I properly document and bill E/M visits in my EHR?',
'2021 E/M guidelines simplified code selection based on MDM or time: Medical decision making has three elements where two of three determine level. (1) Number and complexity of problems: self-limited (1=low), stable chronic (2=low), chronic with exacerbation (1=moderate), acute severe or chronic severe (1=high), undiagnosed uncertain prognosis (moderate to high). (2) Amount and complexity of data: minimal (none), limited (1 test), moderate (3 points from external records=2, interpretation, discussion), extensive (2 of 3 categories). (3) Risk: minimal (OTC meds), low (stable prescriptions), moderate (new prescriptions, minor surgery decision), high (intensive drug monitoring, major surgery decision). MDM levels yield codes: 99202/99212=straightforward, 99203/99213=low, 99204/99214=moderate, 99205/99215=high. Time-based coding uses total time on date including face-to-face and non-face-to-face: 99212=10-19min, 99213=20-29min, 99214=30-39min, 99215=40-54min. Prolonged service 99417 adds for 15+ minutes beyond 99205/99215 thresholds. EHR templates should include MDM calculator auto-suggesting codes, problem list integration marking which addressed, data review tracking with checkboxes for labs and external records reviewed, risk documentation prompts for prescription changes, time tracking with timer features, and audit-ready documentation showing MDM components clearly. Common pitfalls include under-documentation where MDM high but insufficient documentation supports it, over-coding without justification creating audit risk, cloning by copy-forwarding identical content, insufficient problem specificity just listing without addressing, and time documentation errors not including total time or activities. Compliance requires documentation clear and legible, supporting code selected, dated with provider identity, electronically signed, and linked to diagnosis codes. Audit protection needs MDM elements explicitly documented, clinical thought process clear, data review specific, risks addressed, time documented if time-based with activities described, and no cloning with unique visit elements. Templates by visit type include wellness visits with age-appropriate screenings, chronic care management with problem-focused assessment for each condition, acute visits with chief complaint and treatment plan, and follow-up visits assessing status and response to treatment. Prolonged services 99417 bill when total time exceeds 99205 75+ minutes or 99215 55+ minutes requiring first 15 minutes additional for 1 unit and each additional 15 minutes for another unit with total time and activities documented.',
'2021 E/M guidelines - code by MDM or time: MDM LEVELS (2 of 3): (1) PROBLEMS: self-limited (1=low), stable chronic (2=low), exacerbation (1=moderate), severe/undiagnosed (1=high). (2) DATA: minimal (none), limited (1 test), moderate (3 points - external records=2 + interpretation/discussion), extensive (2 of 3 categories). (3) RISK: minimal (OTC), low (stable rx), moderate (new rx, minor surgery), high (intensive monitoring, major surgery). CODES: 99202/99212=straightforward, 99203/99213=low, 99204/99214=moderate, 99205/99215=high. TIME: total on date (face-to-face + non), 99214=30-39min, 99215=40-54min, prolonged 99417=15+min beyond. EHR: MDM calculator, problem list integration, data review tracking, time timer, audit-ready. Avoid: under-documentation, over-coding, cloning, vague problems. Document specifics: tests with findings, external records source/date, prescription changes, time with activities. Counseling >50%=time-based.',
482, ARRAY['E/M coding', 'evaluation management', '99214', '99213', 'MDM medical decision making', 'time-based E/M']);

INSERT INTO specialty_faqs (specialty_slug, category, question, answer, short_answer, priority, search_keywords) VALUES
('general', 'technology', 'What are best practices for EHR implementation to ensure billing success?',
'Successful EHR implementation requires billing workflow planning from day one: Pre-implementation planning includes vendor selection evaluating integrated billing modules, specialty-specific features, interoperability with clearinghouses, reporting capabilities, and compliance features. Project team needs executive sponsor, project manager, clinical champion, billing manager, IT lead, trainers, and vendor team. Workflow analysis documents current state including registration, scheduling, clinical documentation, charge capture process and timing, claims submission methods, payment posting manual or automated, denial management, and AR follow-up identifying bottlenecks and inefficiencies. Implementation phases include Configuration taking 3-6 months for system setup of demographics and insurance with payer lists and IDs, provider and facility details with NPI and taxonomy, charge master with CPT codes and fee schedules, diagnosis codes with common favorites, templates and forms for clinical and billing, claims generation with scrubbing rules, ERA posting with auto-posting rules and adjustment code mapping, and reporting with standard and custom reports. Interface and Integration connects clearinghouse for claims transmission and eligibility, lab interfaces for orders and results, pharmacy ePrescribe, HIE connectivity, and practice management if separate. Training 2-4 weeks before go-live includes provider training 4-8 hours on documentation and charge capture, front office training 4-6 hours on registration and eligibility, billing staff training 8-12 hours on charges through reporting, and super-user training 8-16 hours for advanced support. Go-live uses big bang all-at-once or phased by location with on-site vendor and super-user support, command center for issues, provider support with possible scribes and extended schedules, and billing support with double-checking and daily reconciliation. Stabilization 1-3 months post includes workflow refinement, training reinforcement, revenue cycle monitoring of charge lag daily and denials compared to baseline, and issue resolution. Billing success factors require charge capture workflow design with same-day entry goal, daily claims submission with auto-batching and scrubbing, ERA auto-posting carefully configured with matching rules and adjustment codes mapped, and systematic denial management with root cause analysis. Common pitfalls include insufficient training without hands-on practice, inadequate configuration with generic templates, poor workflow design not matching practice flow, unrealistic timeline rushing implementation, lack of super-users creating vendor dependency, ignoring provider input causing resistance, and inadequate go-live support. Revenue impact management expects temporary decline with charge lag increasing and claim submission slowing, mitigated by building 3-6 months cash reserve, aggressive pre-AR collection, temporary over-staffing, daily charge reconciliation, and close monitoring. Metrics for success include charge lag under 1 day, claim submission under 2 days, clean claim rate over 95%, denial rate under 5%, and AR days maintained or improved.',
'EHR implementation billing success: PRE-IMPLEMENTATION: vendor selection (integrated billing, specialty features, interoperability), project team (sponsor, PM, clinical champion, billing manager, IT), workflow analysis (current state, pain points, future design). CONFIGURATION: payer list + IDs, provider NPI/taxonomy, charge master CPT/fees, templates with charge capture, claims rules, ERA auto-posting + code mapping. INTEGRATION: clearinghouse (837/835/270/271/276/277), lab HL7, ePrescribe, HIE. TRAINING: providers (documentation, charges, 4-8hrs), front office (registration, eligibility, 4-6hrs), billing (charges, claims, ERA, denials, 8-12hrs), super-users (advanced, 8-16hrs). GO-LIVE: on-site support, command center, phased or big bang. STABILIZATION: workflow refinement, monitoring (charge lag daily, denials vs baseline). KEY: same-day charges, daily claims, ERA configured, denial system. EXPECT: temporary dip 1-2 months, mitigate with cash reserve, daily reconciliation. METRICS: charge lag <1 day, claims <2 days, clean claim >95%, denials <5%.',
483, ARRAY['EHR implementation', 'EHR go-live billing', 'implement EHR', 'EHR training', 'charge capture implementation']);

INSERT INTO specialty_faqs (specialty_slug, category, question, answer, short_answer, priority, search_keywords) VALUES
('general', 'technology', 'How do I train my staff on EHR billing functionality?',
'Comprehensive EHR billing training by role ensures success: Training philosophy follows adult learning with relevance connecting to daily work, hands-on active practice, reinforcement through multiple methods, and customization for roles and skill levels. Provider training focuses on clinical documentation with template navigation and smart text, charge capture with CPT code selection and diagnosis linking, coding guidelines for E/M documentation and medical necessity, orders and prescriptions, and quality compliance. Duration 4-8 hours initially plus monthly tips 15-30 minutes and quarterly updates. Methods include classroom didactic 2-4 hours, hands-on lab 2-4 hours in practice environment, at-the-elbow go-live support, video tutorials for reference, and quick reference cards. Provider engagement emphasizes benefits of efficiency, better patient care, revenue capture, and compliance protection. Front office staff training covers patient registration with demographics and insurance card scanning, scheduling with appointment types and resources, insurance verification using real-time 270/271 eligibility, check-in with copay collection, and check-out with follow-up appointments. Duration 4-6 hours initially plus quarterly updates. Methods include classroom overview, hands-on practice with scenarios, shadowing experienced staff, and role-playing. Billing staff training most complex at 8-12 hours covers charge entry and review, claims management with batching and scrubbing, payment posting with ERA monitoring and exceptions, denial management with reason code interpretation and appeals, AR follow-up with aging analysis, and reporting. Ongoing monthly meetings 1-2 hours and annual coding updates. Methods include classroom comprehensive overview, intensive hands-on in practice environment, on-the-job apprenticeship 2-4 weeks, and certification support for CPC/CPB/CCS. Billing staff competencies require coding proficiency in CPT/ICD-10, payer knowledge of policies and requirements, system expertise with advanced skills, regulations and compliance understanding, and professional communication. Super-users selected as internal experts receive intensive 16-24 hours training for advanced features, troubleshooting, train-the-trainer skills, and vendor relationships with responsibilities supporting colleagues, testing system changes, delivering training, identifying optimizations, and serving as liaison between users and IT. Training content development includes core curriculum on system basics, workflows, specialty-specific requirements, compliance and security, and patient interaction. Materials include comprehensive training manual, laminated quick reference cards, video library with 3-5 minute focused tutorials, online searchable knowledge base, and practice environment available 24/7. Continuous improvement uses feedback loops with regular check-ins and satisfaction surveys, advanced training for proficient users at 3-6 months, and updates for system releases and regulatory changes. Success measured by knowledge metrics of assessment scores over 80% and certification rates, performance metrics of improving charge lag and coding accuracy, and efficiency metrics of decreasing documentation time and training needs.',
'EHR billing training by role: PROVIDERS: documentation (templates, smart text), charge capture (CPT selection, diagnosis linking, modifiers), E/M coding (MDM vs time), 4-8hrs initial + monthly tips + quarterly updates. Methods: classroom, hands-on lab, at-the-elbow, videos, quick-reference. Emphasize efficiency/revenue benefits. FRONT OFFICE: registration (demographics, insurance), scheduling, eligibility verification (real-time 270/271), copay collection, 4-6hrs + quarterly. Methods: hands-on, shadowing, role-playing. BILLING STAFF: charge entry/review, claims (batch, scrubbing), ERA posting (auto + exceptions), denials (CARC/RARC, appeals), AR follow-up, reporting, 8-12hrs + monthly meetings + annual coding updates. Methods: classroom, intensive hands-on, apprenticeship 2-4 weeks, certification support (CPC/CPB). SUPER-USERS: advanced 16-24hrs, support colleagues, testing, training delivery, optimization. MATERIALS: manual, quick-reference, video library, practice environment. CONTINUOUS: feedback, advanced training 3-6 months, updates. METRICS: charge lag <1 day, coding >95%, denials <5%.',
484, ARRAY['EHR training', 'train staff EHR billing', 'provider training', 'billing staff training', 'super-user']);

INSERT INTO specialty_faqs (specialty_slug, category, question, answer, short_answer, priority, search_keywords) VALUES
('general', 'coding', 'How do I use EHR templates to capture specialty-specific billing requirements?',
'Specialty-specific EHR templates optimize documentation and billing: Template principles include procedure-focused for surgical specialties documenting pre-procedure indication and consent, intra-procedure technique and findings with implant lot numbers, and post-procedure status and global period with billing elements of CPT auto-suggested and modifiers auto-applied RT/LT/50/22/62. Time-based templates for psychiatry and therapy feature prominent time tracking with start/stop timer, activities documented justifying time, code selection automatic based on thresholds like 99214 for 30-39 minutes or 90834 psychotherapy, and compliance ensured. Disease-focused templates for chronic care use problem-oriented structure with active problem list driving content, each problem addressed with assessment and plan, guideline-driven order sets, medication management emphasized with reconciliation, and care coordination documented for referrals and education. Specialty examples include cardiology with diagnostic testing templates capturing echo measurements and cath findings for complex procedure codes 93451-93464, orthopedics with body diagrams for injury location, fracture classification auto-coding, implant barcode scanning, and laterality enforcement for RT/LT modifiers, dermatology with lesion counter tracking multiple lesions and treatments, size calculator for excision codes 11400-11646 by size, photo integration before/after, and destruction grouping first lesion 17000 plus additional 17003, mental health with timer central showing thresholds, mental status exam structured checkboxes, safety assessment required for self-harm risk, and DSM-5 diagnosis ICD-10 codes, and physical therapy with 8-minute rule calculator ensuring compliance, progress tracking measurements for ROM and strength charting medical necessity, goal setting with SMART functional goals, and treatment plan documentation. Template design process involves needs assessment reviewing specialty billing requirements and common CPT codes, template build with structured data fields and smart text macros including conditional logic and required fields with charge capture integrated, testing with champion pilots using 2-4 weeks with billing validation, and rollout with comprehensive training, monitoring, and quarterly optimization. Compliance considerations prevent cloning with visit-specific unique elements, ensure medical necessity statements and linked diagnoses, require electronic signatures with attestation, and maintain documentation standards with clear rationale and audit trails. Ongoing maintenance includes annual code updates with new CPT January 1 and ICD-10 October 1, payer policy changes incorporating LCD/NCD updates, continuous provider feedback addressing frustrations, and compliance updates for coding guidelines and NCCI edits. ROI of specialty templates includes improved revenue from appropriate code capture without undercoding, faster documentation with templates and macros, fewer denials from complete accurate documentation, and audit protection with comprehensive support for codes billed. Investment of 10-40 hours initial build plus 4-8 hours provider training and 2-4 hours quarterly maintenance returns typical $50K-200K increased annual revenue from better charge capture and reduced denials plus time savings and reduced compliance risk.',
'Specialty-specific EHR templates optimize billing: PRINCIPLES: (1) PROCEDURE-FOCUSED (surgical): pre-procedure (indication, consent, H&P, time-out), intra-procedure (technique, findings, specimens, implants/lot#, time, assistants), post-procedure (status, complications, global period). Billing: CPT auto-suggested, modifiers (RT/LT/50/22/62), diagnosis linked, supply charges. (2) TIME-BASED (psychiatry, therapy, critical care): timer start/stop, activities documented, code auto by time threshold (99214=30-39min, 90834 psychotherapy), compliance. (3) DISEASE-FOCUSED (chronic care): problem list drives template, guideline orders, medication reconciliation, care coordination, MDM for E/M level, CCM/TCM captured, MIPS. SPECIALTY EXAMPLES: cardiology (echo measurements, cath findings, 93451-93464), orthopedics (body diagrams, fracture classification, implant barcode, RT/LT, 11400-17286), dermatology (lesion counter, size calculator, photos, destruction first+additional), mental health (timer, mental status exam, DSM-5, 90832/90834/90837), PT (8-minute rule calculator, progress tracking, SMART goals, 97110-97164). DESIGN: needs assessment, structured fields + smart text + conditional logic, required fields, charge capture integrated, pilot, training. COMPLIANCE: no cloning, medical necessity, signature. MAINTENANCE: annual codes (CPT Jan 1, ICD-10 Oct 1), payer changes, feedback. ROI: $50K-200K revenue increase.',
485, ARRAY['specialty EHR templates', 'procedure templates', 'EHR customization', 'cardiology templates', 'orthopedic templates', 'psychotherapy templates', 'PT billing templates']);
